observations.recommendation:
We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendation that the LCE ensure strict adherence to the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445, Section 5.7 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Section 1.1 of COA Circular No. 2012 – 001 dated June 14, 2012 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to cause the immediate liquidation/settlement of all cash advances;

Ensure that no additional cash advance shall be granted if the previous cash advances have not been liquidated/accounted;

Require the former officials and employees of the LGU to immediately settle their unliquidated cash advances through the issuance of demand letters;

Withhold the salaries of officials and employees whose cash advances remained unliquidated; and 

Take appropriate administrative action against the official/employee for non-compliance.

We recommended that Management:
Require the BAC and the BAC Secretariat to include all procurement activities in the APP and the mode of procurement to be used for proper planning, monitoring of procurements and sound fiscal management;
Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to see to it that the ObR is duly signed by the MBO before certifying the completeness of supporting documents in the DV;
Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to issue checks directly to suppliers to pay financial transactions and avoid payments through cash advance and reimbursements in compliance with Sections 2 and 3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 to withhold taxes thereof;
Require the MBO, in coordination with the Acting Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer, to refrain from using the TF to other purpose other than its specific for which it is intended;
Require the BAC, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat, to post all NOA, contract, or PO on the website of the LGU or any conspicuous place in the premises of the PE and GPPB online portal for Emergency Procurement under the Bayanihan Act for information purposes and to require the submission of the mandatory documentary requirements from the suppliers, distributors, manufacturers or contractors concerned;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant, LDRRMO and Municipal Engineer to submit the list of affected families and proof of receipt of distribution of relief goods and other supporting documents; and
Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to require the supplier of the sacks of rice to provide the Sales Invoices for the payments made.

We recommended that Management:
Require the MSWDO to submit the Certificate of Eligibility duly signed by her and the LCE;
Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the MSWDO, to submit the copy of valid ID, Barangay Certification with specimen signature of the beneficiary and the certificate of eligibility of the 72 beneficiaries in Barangay Tiep for further evaluation of the Audit Team;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Audit Team with the payroll duly signed by all payees and the authorization letters of claimants other than the payee, and
Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant, with the Assistance of the MSWDO, to issue demand letters to the ten beneficiaries.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to notify the officials and employees concerned and cause the refund of the amount paid in excess of the available appropriation provided for the COVID-19 Hazard Pay by requiring the Acting Municipal Accountant to notify the officials and employees concerned;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Human Resource and Management Officer (HRMO), to submit the DTRs, ARs for JO workers and authorization to physically report to work for further evaluation of the Audit Team;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Audit Team with the payroll duly signed by all payees and the authorization letters of claimants other than the payee; and
Require the MBO to refrain from charging hazard pay of JO workers against the Personnel Services of the LGU and observe to the provision of Section 7.0 of DBM BC No. 2020-01 in providing funds thereof.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC to duly accomplish Section V (Special Conditions of the Contract) of the bidding documents to ensure that the contract specific requirements of the project are properly disclosed and to invite representatives from National Associations of Contractors duly recognized by the Construction Industry Authority of the Philippines as observer in all stages of the procurement;
Instruct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that all advertisements and posting of Invitation to Bid are correct for accurate information to prospective bidders and to disclose in the certifications of posting the NOA and NTP to conspicuous places the period when it was posted for complete information;
Require the BAC, in coordination with the TWG Members, to duly indicate the parties consulted in the validation of the documents submitted by the bidder and to include in the Post-Qualification Evaluation Report actions taken in the verification of concerned regulatory bodies, validation of competence, experience and availability of the bidder and inspection and testing of capacities of the equipment to be used or leased in the project;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the BAC, to submit the lacking documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team; and
Require the Municipal Engineer to intensify monitoring of completion of projects within the target date to avoid recurrence of negative slippage and to submit the written order of suspension and order to resume work for further evaluation of the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC to duly accomplish Section V, Special Conditions of the Contract and Section VI, Schedule of Requirements of the bidding documents to ensure that the contract specific requirements and delivery schedule of the projects are properly disclosed, to conduct Pre-bid Conference on projects with ABC of ₱1,000,000.00 or more to clarify and/or explain any of the requirements, terms, conditions, and specifications stipulated in the Bidding Documents and to invite representative from specific relevant chamber-member of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry as observer on all stages of the procurement;
Require the BAC, with the assistance of the TWG Members, to include in the Post-Qualification Evaluation Report actions taken in the verification of delay in partial delivery for ongoing government and private contracts, bidder’s failure to deliver or perform any or all of the goods or services within the period specified in the contract and unsatisfactory performance of the supplier’s obligation as per contract terms and conditions at the time of inspection;
Require the BAC Secretariat to post the NOA in the PhilGEPS within three days from its issuance and to disclose in the certifications of posting the NOA and NTP to conspicuous places the date of posting thereof for complete information; and
Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant and the BAC to submit the lacking documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to verify the completeness of supporting documents before affixing his signature in the DV for the payment of wages of JO Workers;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the HRMO, to provide their basis in computing the number of days paid in the payroll of wages of JO Workers and to submit the required documents on the deficiencies observed for further evaluation of the Audit Team and;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer, with the assistance of the Acting Municipal Accountant, to furnish the Audit Team with the copy of payroll duly signed by all payees and the authorization letters of claimants other than the payee.

We recommended that Management:
Require the MSWMB to include as members the Chairperson of the Sangguniang Kabataan Federation, a representative from NGOs whose principal purpose is to promote recycling and the protection of air and water quality, a representative from the recycling industry and a representative from the manufacturing or packaging industry for viable inputs in the plans and targets of the MSWMB;
Instruct the MSWMB to facilitate the revisions and updating of data required for the completion and approval of the ten-year solid waste management plan;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Sanitary Inspector, to impose violation and penalty fees in accordance with Section 38, Article X of the Municipal Ordinance No. 5, Series of 2004; and
Direct the BAC to provide the details of description/specification of dump trucks, total distance to be covered in the complete route and estimated volume in cubic meters of garbage to be hauled from the area, including the basis for estimates for in the contract agreement for the rental of trucks and driving services for clear and complete information on the conditions agreed upon.

We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendation that the Local Chief Executive ensure strict adherence to the provisions of Section 89 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445, Section 5.7 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Section 1.1 of COA Circular No. 2012 – 001 dated June 14, 2012 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to cause the immediate liquidation/settlement of all cash advances;
Ensure that no additional cash advance shall be granted if the previous cash advances have not been liquidated/accounted;
Require the former officials and employees of the LGU to immediately settle their unliquidated cash advances through the issuance of demand letters;
Withhold the salaries of officials and employees whose cash advances remained unliquidated; and
Take appropriate administrative action against the official/employee for non-compliance.

We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the Municipal Accountant to:
Issue demand letters to officials and employees concerned of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances and employees who were already resigned or transferred to other office, to cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Require the municipal officials and employees concerned including the Municipal Accountant to liquidate/settle their cash advances immediately.
Ensure the completeness of required supporting documents in the processing of claims in the granting of cash advances;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advance to official and employee unless the previous cash advance granted them have been liquidated;
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of the abovementioned Circulars to avoid the penalty stated thereon; and
We further, recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Treasurer to withhold the salaries of the municipal officials and employees concerned with unliquidated cash advances pursuant to Section 9 of COA Circular No. 2012-004 considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate their cash advances.

We have recommended that management:
Ensure compliance with the provisions of DBM Budget Circular No. 2004-5A and 2007-3 on the payment of honoraria to BAC members, BAC Secretariat and TWG members;
Explain the payments of such honoraria and provide the computation and required documentation in accordance with the above laws, rules and regulations for all the payments in order to complete our audit decision;
Cause the refund of excess payments of honoraria to BAC members, BAC Secretariat and TWG Members.
